{
  "text": "Allergic reactions are manifestations of atopy, hereditary disposition to develop hypersensitivity to environmental substances (e.g., pollen, dander, etc.) [CITATION_1] . Three main manifestations of atopy are AD (atopic dermatitis), a chronic skin condition, AR (allergic rhinitis) mostly seasonal respiratory condition, and AA (allergic asthma). Psychological studies found that chronic stress plays an important role in onset and pathogenesis of allergies [CITATION_2] . Based on concept of allostasis [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , chronic exposure to stress leads to accumulation of allostatic load, which can be linked to physiological changes, as well as psychological states (e.g., anxiety). Allostatic load can result in various dysregulations of allostatic systems, nervous, endocrine and immune system. Studies of neuroendocrine HPA (hypothalamus-pituitary-adrenal) axis in allergy [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] found lowered levels of salivary cortisol in response to psychosocial stress in patients with AD [CITATION_7] and AR [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . One of possible mechanisms of hypocortisolism is it being a result of chronic activation of HPA axis and, therefore, its inhibition through feedback regulation [CITATION_10] . Similarly, autonomic nervous system dysregulation was described, however, while some studies showed sympathetic over-activation in allergy [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] , other studies documented parasympathetic predominance [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] [CITATION_17] .",
